--- !u!114 &1257194685
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1257194681}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 45bb53396fcdfb844b3acbabe4f24240, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::IntroScript
  textComponent: {fileID: 1751818837}
  lines:
  - The Royal Navy remains the world's most powerful fleet, but the "Two-Power Standard"
    is becoming an expensive obsession. To our East, the German High Seas Fleet grows
    with every passing year, forcing us into a ruinous arms race. Meanwhile, the
    Army is in the midst of a painful transformation. No longer just a colonial police
    force, it is being restructured into a professional expeditionary force... The
    horizon is no longer empty... The Pax Britannica is no longer a given.
  - The era of "Splendid Isolation" has concluded, replaced by a network of Continental
    alliances. Our security is now tied to the interests of France and Russia, our
    former rivals, in an attempt to balance the growing power of the Triple Alliance.
    British foreign policy is no longer independent. Our diplomatic reach is increasingly
    overextended by the need to manage European stability. We are the masters of
    an Empire upon which the sun never sets, yet we find ourselves watching the shadows
    grow longer across Europe.
  - 'Our industrial supremacy is being overtaken by the rapid modernization of Germany
    and the United States. While the City of London sees record turnover, our domestic
    manufacturing base is aging and facing calls for "Imperial Preference" tariffs
    to survive. Compounding this is the "Social Question": the demand for expensive
    state-funded pensions and insurance. We are a land of staggering plenty, built
    upon a foundation that has finally started to tremble.'
  - The machinery of British governance is currently paralyzed. The House of Lords
    is in open defiance of the Commons, vetoing budgets and breaking the long-standing
    convention of parliamentary supremacy. The Suffragettes have moved from petitions
    to direct action, while the "Irish Question" threatens to trigger a sectarian
    civil war. The old Liberal-Conservative duopoly is fracturing, and the emergence
    of the Labour Party has introduced a permanent element of class-based friction
    into Westminster. The velvet glove of tradition is wearing through, but the question
    remains... will it be thrown out?
  images:
  - {fileID: 394347172}
  - {fileID: 374704245}
  - {fileID: 1893647676}
  - {fileID: 2101642968}
  textSpeed: 0.05
  sceneName: SampleScene_V2
  timeline: {fileID: 1224289890}
  fader: {fileID: 1261475296}
  changeTime: 3.01
